Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C.

Halve, peel and chop the @onion{1} into small pieces. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2}(grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @carrot{2}, quarter lengthways and chop into 3cm long batons (no need to peel). Roughly chop the @dill{1/2} (stalks and all).

Roughly chop the @prunes{40}.

Pop the carrots onto a #baking tray{}, season with @salt and @pepper, then toss to coat.

Pop on the top shelf of your oven and roast until golden, ~{20-25%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Pour the @water{240} for the bulgur wheat into a #saucepan{}, bring to the boil and stir in the @bulgur wheat{120} and half the @chicken stock paste{5}.

Bring back up to the boil, simmer for ~{1%minute}, pop a #lid{} on the pan and remove from the heat. Leave to the side for ~{12-15%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, heat a large #frying pan{} (no oil) on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @lamb mince{200}. Season with @salt and @pepper and cook until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break up as it cooks, then drain and discard any excess fat.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Lower the heat to medium and add the @onion{1}(chopped). Cook until soft, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Stir in the @garlic{2%cloves}(grated), @tomato puree{30} and @shawarma seasoning mix{1}. Cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Add the @water{100} for the lamb, along with the remaining @chicken stock paste{5} and the prunes. Stir together and bring to a gentle simmer.

Cook until the mixture is thick, ~{5-7%minutes}. Season to taste with @salt and @pepper if needed.

> IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, mix the @low fat natural yoghurt{75} with half of the dill. Season with @salt and @pepper.

Fluff up the bulgur wheat with a #fork{} and stir through the @sumac{1} and the remaining dill. Serve in #bowls{} with the Lebanese style lamb on top.

Finish with some roasted carrots and a spoonful of dill yoghurt. Enjoy!